title: For Sale:  Colt Magnum Carry 357 Mag Stainless Revolver
postcontent: Colt Magnum Carry 357 Mag, 2 inch Barrel, Factory Hogue Grips. Includes Original Case and Original Instruction Manual.The Colt Magnum Carry 357 was MANUFACTURED ONLY ONE YEAR, 1999. Due to the short production period and the Magnum chambering, the Magnum Carry is rare and sought after by both collectors and shooters wanting a powerful concealed carry revolver. In 1999 Colt introduced their last double action revolver model. This was a version of the SF-VI/DS-II series revolvers built on the "SF-VI" frame. This was a stainless steel revolver using the same transfer bar safety-ignition system as all Colts made after 1969. The new model was chambered for the .357 Magnum cartridge, the first small frame Colt ever to use the Magnum round. The frame was slightly thickened in the top strap area to increase strength and the gun was heat treated to a higher level. Barrels were 2 inches, and a few 3 inch models. Finish was satin stainless and possibly a few bright polish models. The grips were Hogue Mono-Grips made for Colt by Hogue. These have a pebble texture. PRICE: $1895REDACTEDElite Pawn and Gun7804 Garners Ferry RdColumbia, SC 29209

title: For Sale:  Here is what gun control advocates want.
postcontent: The following is a response to a NY Times Editorial and is a gun control advocate being completely honest about the "reasonable gun safety" laws they want:"RogerPhoenix, AZ January 6, 2016 Ok, this is getting ridiculous. Even though President Obama has not managed to get any gun control measures passed in the seven years of his presidency, the sale of guns has increased dramatically on the basis of irrational fear and paranoia. Since the gun lobby refuses to compromise on any reasonable gun laws, it’s time to finally declare, “Yes, we are in fact coming for your guns.” First we’ll outlaw handguns, the main purpose of which is to shoot another human while being easily concealed. Then we will outlaw any type of assault weapon or rifle with a high-capacity magazine. Finally, we will limit and control the amount of ammunition any person can buy. You can still have a simple rifle or shotgun for hunting or protection as you see fit, but even those will have to be safely secured in your home when not in use. How will we accomplish this? With government storm troopers raiding your house? No, we will use the most powerful weapon a democracy has at its disposal, our vote."579 up votesThis is what Obama wants too. This is why he is pushing for expanding the prohibited persons lists to include those on the no-fly list, a list put together with no due process of law at all.The next time somebody says they are not coming for your guns remember this and remember Diane Feinsteins words: "If I could’ve gotten 51 votes in the Senate of the United States for an outright ban, picking up every one of them — Mr. and Mrs. America turn ’em all in — I would have done it. I could not do that. The votes weren’t here." - Diane Feinstein 60 minutes 1995.So called Universal Background Checks, MIGHT be a good idea if they were not such an obvious stepping stone to ever more gun control. The strategy is:1. Force all sales through NICS.2. Change federal law to require firearm data to be sent in NICS transactions and allow a gun owner database to be built from NICS data. This only takes one gun control sympathetic session of congress and a president to sign it.3. Prohibit anyone and everyone possible by expanding the prohibited persons categories. The "no-fly" list is the first step, next comes the "mentally ill" which is every vet with a diagnosis of PTSD, every kid prescribed an ADHD drug and every person who has ever had an outpatient counseling session with a therapist. Next misdemeanors like 1st DUI offense and other traffic offenses. We actually already prohibit many misdemeanor offenders because many state misdemeanors carry a maximum sentence of more than two years which is the threshhold for a state misdemeanor being a prohibiting factor. Many of these misdemeanors are relatively minor charges where judges seldom give any jail time at all but what matters under federal law is the maximum time they could give. 4. Pass any and all possible gun restrictions whether constitutional or not and hope the courts take no action or at least drag it out as long as possible.5. Eliminate protection for firearms manufacturers from lawsuits over product misuse. This one doesn't really require the other stepping stones, but the more people who are ultimately prohibited the less people who will have a right they still deem worth protecting i.e. divide and conquer. For those who think the courts will intercede, consider this: Since the Heller and McDonald decisions, no lower court has overturned any really significant anti-gun legislation and the Supreme court just refused to hear an appeal where the Highland Park (a city near Chicago) Assault weapons ban was upheld, meaning despite clear language from the supreme court protecting firearms in common usage, the ban has been allowed to stand. It's highly doubtful that the courts will protect your rights to anywhere near the degree they are constitutionally required too. Supreme court rulings are of little practical use if even the Supreme court that issued the ruling will not strike down laws contrary to it.
